e Channel]\n*[https://www.pbs.org/soundtracks/  \"Sound Tracks: Music Without Borders\" website]\n*[https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/ \"Frontline World\" website]\n*[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/  \"Frontline\" website]\n*[http://priceofsex.org/ \"Price of Sex\" film website]\n*[https://www.revealnews.org/author/stephen-talbot/ \"Reveal News / Center for Investigative Reporting]\n*[https://www.kqed.org/forum/201205171030/remembering-carlos-fuentes KQED interview on the death of writer Carlos Fuentes. 2012]\n*[https://www.kqed.org/forum/2010101868311/documentary-highlights-impact-of-late-sf-mayor-george-moscone KQED interview on the life and legacy of San Francisco Mayor George Moscone. 2018]\n*[https://www.kqed.org/forum/2010101873925/remembering-the-loma-prieta-earthquake-30-years-on KQED interview on the 30th anniversary of the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake. 2019] \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Talbot, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:People from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Harvard-Westlake School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Stephen Talbot\n| image       = Stephen Talbot seated.jpg\n| imagesize   = 200px\n| caption     = Talbot at UC Berkeley in 2007\n| birth_name  = Stephen Henderson Talbot\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1949|02|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = \n| other_names = Steve Talbot\n| website     = \n| children    = 2\n| spouse      = Pippa Gordon\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Henderson Talbot''' (born February 28, 1949) is an American [[TV documentary]] [[film producer|producer]], [[reporter]], [[writer]], and longtime contributor to the [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS), particularly the series ''[[Frontline (TV series)|Frontline]]''. His more than 40 documentaries include the Frontline films ''The Best Campaign Money Can Buy'', ''The Long March of Newt Gingrich'', ''Justice for Sale'', and ''News War: What's Happening to the News''. Talbot has also written and produced PBS biographies of writers Dashiell Hammett, Beryl Markham, Ken Kesey, Carlos Fuentes, Maxine Hong Kingston and John Dos Passos. He was co-creator and executive producer of the PBS music specials, ''[[Sound Tracks: Music Without Borders]]'', and an online series of music videos ''Quick Hits''.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.current.org/music/music1118soundtracks.html |title='Sound Tracks' proposed for PBS, 2011 |publisher=Current.org |date=2011-09-19 |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> \n\nHe began his career in broadcast journalism as a reporter and producer at KQED-TV in San Francisco, where he also contributed feature news stories to the MacNeil/Lehrer NewsHour.<ref>https://americanarchive.org/catalog?q=stephen+talbot&utf8=\u2713&f[access_types][]=online</ref> Talbot has also worked as a producer and senior producer for the [[Center for Investigative Reporting]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revealnews.org/author/stephen-talbot/ |title=The Center for Investigative Reporting}}</ref> \n\nBefore becoming a journalist and documentary producer, Talbot was a [[television]] [[child actor]] in the late 1950s and early 1960s. He is known for his role in the TV [[sitcom]] ''[[Leave It to Beaver]]'', in which he played [[Gilbert Bates (Leave It to Beaver character)|Gilbert Bates]], friend of [[Theodore Cleaver|Theodore \"Beaver\" Cleaver]] ([[Jerry Mathers]]).<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010|date=2011|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7|page=591|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in Hollywood and raised in Studio City, California, Stephen Talbot is the son of [[Lyle Talbot]], a film and TV actor, and Paula Talbot (born Margaret Epple).<ref>{{cite news|author=Mel Gussow |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/03/05/arts/lyle-talbot-94-charactor-actor-and-tv-neighbor.html |title=Lyle Talbot, 94, Charactor {{sic|nolink=y}} Actor And TV Neighbor |newspaper=The New York Times |date=1996-03-05 |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> Stephen Talbot graduated from Harvard High School (now called [[Harvard-Westlake]]) in 1966.<ref name=\"Day Beaver Died\" /> In 1970, he graduated from [[Wesleyan University]] in Connecticut, where he studied English and film and was very active in anti-Vietnam war protests.<ref name=\"Day Beaver Died\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13809968/jerry-mathers-died-steve-talbot|title=The Day the Beaver Died: Reflections on Becoming an Anti-War Activist|date=October 1, 2017|publisher=KQED}}</ref> He began making films about the anti-war movement, including ''March on Washington'', ''DC III'' (about [[Vietnam Veterans Against the War]]), and ''[[Year of the Tiger (film)|Year of the Tiger]]'' filmed in Vietnam. From 1970 to 1973, he worked at the State University of New York College at Old Westbury, then an experimental college on Long Island; he began as assistant to the school's president and subsequently became a lecturer in the American Studies program.\n\n==Acting career==\nTalbot's first appearance as Gilbert on [[Leave it to Beaver]] was in a 1959 episode called \"Beaver and Gilbert\", where he plays an insecure new kid in town who is prone to telling tall tales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0630183/|title=Beaver and Gilbert|date=March 19, 1959|publisher=IMDb}}</ref> Early on in the series, the Gilbert character was someone constantly getting the hapless Beaver into trouble. \"I may be a dirty rat, but I'm not a dumb rat,\" Gilbert once declared. But as the series went on Gilbert became a more genuine friend of the Beav, really his closest friend, as seen in episodes like \"Beaver on TV\" (1963) when Gilbert is the only one to believe Beaver had been on a local TV show that did not air live as everyone expected (it had been taped for later broadcast, a new concept at the time).<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0630188/]</ref>\n\nHaving spent his early years in front of the cameras on ''Leave it to Beaver'' as Gilbert Bates (56 episodes), Talbot abandoned acting for a career as a journalist. In an article for [[Salon.com]] in 1997, he looked back with a sense of humor about his past role.\n\n<blockquote>In the interests of historical accuracy I should say that, yes, Gilbert was a troublemaker and an occasional liar, but my character was certainly no Eddie Haskell \u2013 that leering teenage hypocrite who spoke unctuously to parents ('Well, hello Mrs. Cleaver, and how is young Theodore today?') and venomously to the Beav ('Hey, squirt, take a powder before I squash you like a bug').\"!<ref name=\"talbot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/aug97/mothers/beaver970822.html|title=Living Down Beaver|last=Talbot|first=Stephen|work=Salon|accessdate=2006-10-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205114704/https://www.salon.com/aug97/mothers/beaver970822.html|archivedate=2007-02-05}}</ref> \"I have spent my adult life trying to conceal my ''Leave it to Beaver'' past or correcting the historical record. Either way the series has become inescapable. When I was a kid, I loved acting; in fact, I badgered my father and mother until they allowed me to work. But how could I have known as an innocent 9-year-old that I was taking part in a television program that would live on for 40 years as an icon for baby boomers? In the early '80s, I turned down an offer to revive my role as Gilbert in a [[The New Leave It to Beaver|dreadful ''Beaver'' reunion series]]. \"I'm trying to establish myself as a documentary filmmaker and an investigative reporter,\" I explained to the producers. \"I can't go back to being Gilbert!\"<ref name=\"talbot\" />\n</blockquote>\n\nTalbot guest-starred on many television programs in the late 1950s and early 1960s, including three episodes of ''[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]'', ''[[M Squad]]'', ''[[The Barbara Stanwyck Show]]'', ''[[The Blue Angels (TV series)|The Blue Angels]]'', ''[[Men Into Space]]'', ''[[Lawman (TV series)|Lawman]]'', ''[[Wanted: Dead or Alive (TV series)|Wanted: Dead or Alive]]'', ''[[Law of the Plainsman]]'', ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'', ''[[Mr. Novak]]'' and ''[[The Lucy Show]]''. He appeared in comedy sketches with [[Bob Newhart]] in the early '60s NBC variety program, ''[[The Bob Newhart Show (1961 TV series)|The Bob Newhart Show]]''. Talbot played the role of Ronnie Kramer in the [[Columbia Broadcasting System|CBS]]'s [[anthology series]] ''[[The DuPont Show with June Allyson]]'' episode \"Hit and Run\". Talbot also appeared in two episodes of ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'': \"[[Static (The Twilight Zone)|Static]]\" and \"[[The Fugitive (The Twilight Zone)|The Fugitive]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Stephen Talbot|publisher=IMDb |url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0847972/|accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, he was cast as Ab Martin, a grade-school pupil in the episode \"The Twister\" of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]/[[Warner Brothers]] [[Western (genre)|western]] series, ''[[Sugarfoot]]'', with [[Will Hutchins]] in the title role. In the episode, he recites to his dying teacher, Roy Cantwell (Fred Beir) a part of [[Patrick Henry]]'s 1775 address at [[St. John's Episcopal Church (Richmond, Virginia)|St. Johns' Church]]. The \"twister\" in the title of the episode is a [[tornado]] that wipes out a western town.\n\nIn 1960, he played Jimmie Kendall, son of the title character in [[CBS]]'s ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' in the episode, \"The Case of the Wandering Widow\".\n\nOn stage, Talbot co-starred as \"Sonny\" in [[William Inge]]'s ''Dark at the Top of the Stairs'' with [[Marjorie Lord]] at the [[La Jolla Playhouse]].\n\nHe also played [[Dick Clark]]'s nephew in the first movie Clark ever acted in, ''Because They're Young'' (1960), a high school melodrama with [[Tuesday Weld]] and music by \"rock 'n roller\" [[Duane Eddy]].\n\n==Journalism==\nAs an adult, Talbot turned from acting to journalism and did not dwell on his ''\"Leave It To Beaver\"'' heritage, turning down numerous ''LITB'' reunion offers in order to be taken seriously as a reporter.<ref>https://www.salon.com/1997/08/23/beaver970822/</ref> But in recent years he has reflected affectionately on his \"Beaver\" experience in articles and interviews and even in a ''Frontline'' documentary, \"Diet Wars.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/diet/etc/talbot.html |title=Confessions Of A Frontline Dieter &#124; Diet Wars |work=Frontline |publisher=PBS |date=2004-04-08 |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> His articles have appeared in [[Salon.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/writer/stephen_talbot/|title=Stephen Talbot|date=|publisher=Salon.com|accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> the ''[[Washington Post Magazine]]'', ''[[The Nation]]'', ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/media/2012/05/carlos-fuentes-interview|title=Carlos Fuentes: The Mother Jones Interview|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'', the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', and the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Talbot wrote about [[Robert Mugabe]] in an article for the ''Frontline/World'' website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/zimbabwe504/profile.html|work=FRONTLINE/WORLD |title=Zimbabwe - Shadows and Lies: Recollections of Robert Mugabe |publisher=PBS |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> He wrote about \"Leave it to Beaver\" and becoming an anti-war activist for KQED's website.<ref name=\"Day Beaver Died\" />\n\nIn the 1970s, he was a reporter and editor for [[Internews]], a radio and print foreign news service based in [[Berkeley, California]].\n\n==KQED==\nIn the 1980s, Talbot was a staff reporter and producer at [[KQED (TV)|KQED-TV]], the PBS affiliate in San Francisco.\n\nEarly in his career at KQED, Talbot produced two national PBS [[Peabody Award]] winners, ''Broken Arrow'', about [[nuclear weapon]]s accidents,<ref>{{cite web |title=(\"Search Results for 'Broken Arrow'\")\n|url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/results/Broken%20Arrow/1/null/null/title/asc |website=Peabody Awards |publisher=Grady College of Journalism and Mass Communication, University of Georgia |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718021458/http://www.peabodyawards.com/results/Broken%20Arrow/1/null/null/title/asc |archivedate=July 18, 2018}}</ref> and ''The Case of Dashiell Hammett,'' a biography of the crime writer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Current Affairs: The Case of Dashiell Hammett |url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/current-affairsthe-case-of-dashiell-hammett |website=Peabody Awards |publisher=Grady College of Journalism and Mass Communication, University of Georgia |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718022028/http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/current-affairsthe-case-of-dashiell-hammett |archivedate=July 18, 2018}}</ref> \n\nDuring his time at KQED, Talbot produced local documentaries, as well as national PBS documentaries such as ''Namibia: Behind the Lines'', ''South Africa Under Siege'' (a portrait of [[Nelson Mandela]]'s ANC in exile), and ''The Gospel and Guatemala'' with [[Elizabeth Farnsworth]] (an investigation of presidential strongman Efrain Rios Montt and his \"born again\" U.S. supporters). \n\nHe also wrote and produced (or co-produced with Joan Saffa and Judy Flannery) several hour-long PBS biographies of noted writers, including: [[Dashiell Hammett]], [[Ken Kesey]], [[Beryl Markham]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/08/movies/tv-reviews-world-without-walls-about-beryl-markham.html|title=TV REVIEWS - 'World Without Walls,' About Beryl Markham|last=Mitgang|first=Herbert|date=1986-10-08 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> [[Carlos Fuentes]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/05/movies/fuentes-in-a-tv-film-on-life-and-himself.html|title=Fuentes in a TV Film, On Life and Himself|author=Beryl Markham|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/08/movies/tv-reviews-world-without-walls-about-beryl-markham.html|title=TV review of biography of Beryl Markham|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> and [[Maxine Hong Kingston]].\n\nAt KQED, Talbot also reported and produced dozens of feature news stories for ''[[The MacNeil/Lehrer Newshour]]''. \n\nAfter leaving KQED in 1989, Talbot produced and co-wrote a PBS biography of [[John Dos Passos]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/05/arts/tv-weekend-rediscovering-a-30-s-novelist-who-touched-a-generation.html|title=TV WEEKEND; Rediscovering a 30's Novelist Who Touched a Generation|last=Goodman|first=Walter|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nTalbot has returned to KQED over the years to produce documentary specials. In 1991, Talbot investigated the car bomb explosion in Oakland, CA. that nearly killed [[Earth First!]] environmentalist Judi Bari. His documentary, ''Who Bombed Judi Bari?'', critiqued the FBI and Oakland police department charges against her and raised questions about who was responsible for placing the pipe bomb in her car.<ref>Los Angeles Times review|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-06-04-ca-80-story.html</ref> Returning again to KQED in 2001, Talbot wrote and produced a one-hour documentary about [[Jerry Brown#Mayor of Oakland (1999-2007)|Jerry Brown]] as mayor of Oakland, ''The Celebrity and the City''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cironline.org/blog/post/no-2nd-acts-politics-4-clips-look-back-jerry-browns-career-6423|title=Archived copy|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160122062452/http://cironline.org/blog/post/no-2nd-acts-politics-4-clips-look-back-jerry-browns-career-6423|archive-date=2016-01-22|access-date=2017-07-07|df=}}</ref>  He had previously produced a KQED documentary about San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos, \"The Art of Being Mayor.\"\n\n\n==Frontline==\nTalbot has had a long association with ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]'' beginning with his documentary on the financing of the 1992 presidential campaign, ''The Best Campaign Money Can Buy'', which won a [[DuPont Awards|DuPont Award]], and continuing through 2007 with his documentary on the media, ''News War: What's Happening to the News.''\n\nHis other ''Frontline'' news documentaries include \"The Heartbeat of America\" (an investigation of General Motors), \"Public Lands, Private Profits\" (about gold mining on federal land in the West), \"Rush Limbaugh's America\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/28/arts/television-review-what-makes-rush-limbaugh-tick-so-loudly.html|title=TELEVISION REVIEW; What Makes Rush Limbaugh Tick So Loudly - New York Times|author=Walter Goodman|date=1995-02-28 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> \"The Long March of Newt Gingrich\", \"Why America Hates the Press\", \"Spying on Saddam\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/27/arts/television-review-from-alpha-dog-to-wound-licking-in-iraq.html|title=TELEVISION REVIEW; From Alpha Dog to Wound-Licking in Iraq - New York Times|author=Walter Goodman|date=1999-04-27 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> \"Justice for Sale\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.pbs.org/video/1418584020/|title=Video: The Journal: Justice For Sale &#124; Watch Bill Moyers Online &#124; |publisher=PBS Video|date=2010-02-19 |accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> and \"The Battle Over School Choice\".\n\nHis \"[[investigative biography]]\" of [[Newt Gingrich]] \u2013 \"The Long March of Newt Gingrich\" (1995) \u2013 drew renewed interest and was posted with updates on the ''Frontline'' website in 2012 when Gingrich made his unsuccessful bid for the Republican presidential nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/biographies/newt-new/the-long-march-of-newt-gingrich-part-one/|title=The Long March of Newt Gingrich: Part One &#124; The Long March of Newt Gingrich |work=Frontline |author=Sarah Moughty|date=2011-12-19|publisher=PBS|accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Frontline's executive producer [[David Fanning (journalist)|David Fanning]] named Talbot as series editor of ''[[Frontline World]]'', ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]'s'' international news magazine series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/about/blogs/news/frontline-takes-a-world-view-in-new-pbs-series-premiering-thursday-may-23-april-8-2002/|title=Frontline Takes a \"World\" View in New PBS Series Premiering Thursday, May 23 |publisher=PBS}}</ref> Between 2002 and 2008, Talbot oversaw the editorial content of 30 hour-long television episodes and helped commission and supervise nearly 100 broadcast stories. \n\nWith reporter [[Kate Seelye]], Talbot also produced a half-hour FRONTLINE/World story, \"The Earthquake\", about political turmoil in Lebanon and Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/lebanon402/|work=FRONTLINE/WORLD  |title=Lebanon - The Earthquake |date=|publisher=PBS|accessdate=2014-07-04}}</ref> He was senior producer of the Emmy-winning FRONTLINE/World documentary by Gwynne Roberts, ''Iraq: Saddam's Road to Hell'', an investigation of a massacre of Kurds carried out by Saddam Hussein's regime.\n\nWith colleague [[Sharon Tiller]], Talbot also oversaw the Frontline World website and its [[Emmy Award]] and [[Webby Award]]-winning online video series, ''[[Rough Cuts (TV series)|Rough Cuts]]''<ref name=\"SF Chron 20071011\">{{cite news |author=Heidi Benson |date=October 11, 2007 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Frontline-World-video-journalists-bring-world-2497618.php |title='Frontline/World' video journalists bring world to Web|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nBased at [[UC Berkeley]]'s Graduate School of Journalism, Talbot and Tiller taught classes and helped identify and mentor the \"next generation of video journalists\" whose work was showcased on ''Frontline/World''.<ref name=\"SF Chron 20071011\" />\n\n''Frontline World'' won the 2004 [[Overseas Press Club of America]] award for best international TV reporting.\n\n== Sound Tracks ==\nTalbot was also the co-creator and executive producer of ''Sound Tracks: Music Without Borders'', a music show for PBS with host [[Marco Werman]] and reporters Alexis Bloom, Arun Rath and Mirissa Neff. The pilot episode aired in 2010 with stories about the Russian propaganda song \"A Man Like Putin,\" Afrobeat legend Fela Kuti, and \"Borat\" music composer Erran Baron Cohen, and a performance by fado singer Mariza.<ref>[https://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/with-sound-tracks-pbs-appeals-to-music-fans/Content?oid=1564619]</ref>  \n\nA second one-hour episode aired in 2012 with Wynton Marsalis, Youssou N'Dour, Julie Fowlis and Of Monsters and Men.<ref>[https://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Sound-Tracks-review-World-of-musical-riches-3913009.php]</ref> Talbot was also the executive producer of a series of twenty \"Sound Tracks\" online music videos for PBS Digital and YouTube, including interviews with and performances by Levon Helm, Yuja Wang, [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Grimaud]], KT Tunstall, Seun Kuti, Seu Jorge, Anoushka Shankar and Of Monsters and Men.<ref>{{YouTube|user=SoundTracksQH}}</ref>\n\n\n== Public Broadcasting Service (PBS) and Freelance Production ==\nIn addition to his work for KQED and Frontline, Talbot over the years has produced, written or directed a number of specials for \nPBS, as well as producing long and short-form videos for the Center for Investigative Reporting.\n\nFor Oregon Public Broadcasting and PBS, Talbot wrote and directed with David Davis, ''The Sixties: The Years That Shaped a Generation'', a two-hour history special that aired nationally on on PBS in 2005, and was based on his earlier film, ''1968: The Year That Shaped a Generation''(1998.)\n\nHe has executive produced a number of indie documentaries, including ''The Price of Sex'', a documentary by director and photo journalist Mimi Chakarova about sex trafficking in [[Eastern Europe]] and the [[Middle East]]. Chakarova won the 2011 [[Nestor Almendros|Nestor Almendros Award]] for courage in filmmaking from the [[Human Rights Watch|Human Rights Watch Film Festival]] in New York and the [[Daniel Pearl|Daniel Pearl Award]] from the [[International Consortium of Investigative Journalists]].<ref>https://priceofsex.org</ref>\n\nTalbot wrote the one-hour political biography, ''Moscone: A Legacy of Change'' (2018), about San Francisco Mayor George Moscone, \"the people's mayor,\" who was assassinated along with gay Supervisor Harvey Milk in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/moscone-a-legacy-of-change-hlozkc/|title=Moscone: A Legacy of Change - KVIE Documentaries|publisher=PBS}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2012 to 2014, Talbot was senior producer for video projects at the [[Center for Investigative Reporting]], including feature news stories and short documentaries for the PBS Newshour, Univision, KQED-TV in San Francisco and the New York Times. At CIR, Talbot also led the editorial team that created and ran, \"The I Files,\" the first investigative news channel on [[YouTube.com]].\n\nSince 2015, Talbot has been senior producer for documentary shorts at ITVS / Independent Lens (PBS) in San Francisco.\n\nIn 2019 Talbot began co-writing and co-producing the Bay Area NBC series, \"Bay Area Revelations,\" narrated by Peter Coyote, starting with the episodes, \"Exploring Space\"<ref>https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Next-Episode-Exploring-Space-510766371.html</ref> and \"Loma Prieta Earthquake, 30 Years Later\"<ref>https://www.nbcbayarea.com/on-air/as-seen-on/FULL-EPISODE-Loma-Prieta-Earthquake-30-Years-Later_Bay-Area-563079332.html</ref> and continuing in 2020 with \"Female Sports Icons\"<ref>https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/bay-area-revelations/full-episode-female-sports-icons/2220423/</ref> and \"Riding the Waves\" about surfing in Northern California.<ref>https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/bay-area-revelations/bay-area-revelations-riding-the-waves-2/2269243/?fbclid=IwAR1wveSqcehAo8wi7D84FQ-Nwz8ywQf5HUsELU2kZbBo7Q9aCmtJ2h2ltws</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStephen Talbot lives in San Francisco with his wife, Pippa Gordon, a medical social worker. They have a son, Dashiell, and a daughter, Caitlin. They named their son Dashiell, now an attorney, after San Francisco mystery writer Dashiell Hammett. His daughter, Caitlin, graduated with an [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] from [[American Conservatory Theater]], in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite news |author=Steven Winn |date=August 15, 2001 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/Acting-up-ACT-s-Young-Conservatory-students-2888755.php|title=Acting up / ACT's Young Conservatory students have the passion and talent to make it |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> In 2015, he wrote a story, \"Call the Midwife\", reminiscing about the home birth of his daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.kqed.org/stateofhealth/2015/01/28/call-the-midwife-a-home-birth-story/|title=Call the Midwife: A Home Birth Story|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=KQED }}</ref>\n\nTalbot's sister, ''[[New Yorker Magazine|New Yorker]]'' magazine staffer [[Margaret Talbot]], wrote ''The Entertainer: Movies, Magic and My Father's Twentieth Century'' (Riverhead Books, 2012), about their father, [[Lyle Talbot]], and their family history.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Entertainer: Movies, Magic, and My Father's Twentieth Century: Margaret Talbot: 9781594487064: Amazon.com: Books |date=2012-11-08 |isbn=978-1594487064 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/entertainermovie0000talb }}</ref> His brother, [[David Talbot|David]], is the author of several books, including \"Season of the Witch\" about San Francisco in the 1960s and 1970s,  and was the founder and original editor of Salon.com. His sister, Cynthia, is a medical doctor in Portland, Oregon. His nephew, [[Joe Talbot]], won the Best Director prize at Sundance for his debut feature film, ''[[The Last Black Man in San Francisco]]'' (2019).\n\n==Awards==\nTalbot has won numerous awards for his broadcast journalism, including two national [[Emmy Award]]s, four local (San Francisco) Emmys, three Golden Gate Awards from the [[San Francisco International Film Festival]], three [[Thomas M. Storke|Thomas M. Storke International Journalism Awards]] from the [[World Affairs Councils of America|World Affairs Council of Northern California]], three [[Peabody Award]]s, two [[DuPont-Columbia Award|DuPont-Columbia Journalism Silver Batons]], a [[George Polk Award]], an [[Edward Murrow Award (OPC)|Edward R. Murrow Award]] from the Overseas Press Club of America, a First Prize TV Award from the Education Writers Association, a [[National Press Club (United States)|National Press Club]] Arthur Rowse Award for media criticism, and an [[Edgar Allan Poe Award]] from the [[Mystery Writers of America]]. He has been nominated three times for best documentary script writing by the [[Writers Guild of America]].\n\n==Select filmography==\n:See the complete '''Stephen Talbot''' filmography at [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm847972/ ''IMDB'']\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:50%;\"\n|- \"\n! Year !! Title !! Role\n|-\n| 1959 ||  ''[[Leave it to Beaver]]''<br/>1959-1963 56-episodes (TV) || Gilbert Bates\n|-\n| 1960 || ''[[Perry Mason 